Furthermore, we hypothesize that at a city-block level there may be a rich-get-richer effect, which results in popular areas attracting more people per-unit-floor-area. Therefore, in our model, stays are preferentially attracted to areas with larger capacities for that type of stay. This is based on the observation that shops and industries agglomerate due to clustering of economic activities48—for example, resulting in the formation of popular shopping, dining or entertainment districts. To model this, we adopt a two stage process when assigning a stay to a building within a particular tract. Firstly, we spatially group the possible buildings by their centroid coordinates using hierarchical agglomerative clustering and Wards minimal increase of variance method49 to form city-blocks. Then, after probabilistically selecting a block we select an individual building (Fig. 3c). The preferential attraction at the cluster level is given as follows:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
